Robotics RMRC PPA {.title .toc-ignore}
=================

Introduction
------------

This is a term project for an undergraduate Robotics course in the
University of Patras. The objectives are to:

-   Solve the forward kinematics problem.

-   Give an analytic solution for the inverse kinematics problem.

-   Incorporate the Resolved Motion Rate Control (RMRC) algorithm in
    order to create a straight line path witch simulates a welding
    process

We assume that a [KUKA KR 16
R1610-2](https://www.kuka.com/-/media/kuka-downloads/imported/6b77eecacfe542d3b736af377562ecaa/0000321015_en.pdf?rev=20f511ef7e0c47fe987dfa0f848ff85b&hash=AC1B029A917A8FEB6D95DEBFBC2E2873)
is used to complete the task.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Inverse kinematics
------------------

In the inverse kinematics problem we are concerned with finding the
joint angles for a specific pose of the end effector. A modified version
of the solution incorporated by [1] for the Puma 560 robot is used. We
evaluate every solution of the set of eight possible solutions and the
last one is accepted.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

RMRC Algorithm
--------------

Velocities in Joint Space are transformed to Cartesian space by:
\\[\\bar V = J\_v(\\bar q) \\dot {\\bar q}\\] Where \\(\\bar V\\) the
velocity vector of the end effector, \\(\\dot {\\bar q}\\) the joint
space velocity vector and \\(J\_v(\\bar q)\\) the Geometric Jacobian
matrix. Given a nonsingular \\(J\_v(\\bar q)\\) we obtain:

\\[\\dot {\\bar q}= {J\_v}\^{-1}(\\bar q)\\bar V\\] The joint position
vector is given by:

\\[\\bar q = \\bar q\_0 + \\int \_0\^t {\\dot{\\bar q}} dt\\]

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

where subscript i coresponds to initial position and f to final. dt
Is the selected time step.
